Voiceover: So what do we have right here?

00:00:02.545 --> 00:00:05.907
Well this is just a water molecule.

00:00:05.907 --> 00:00:07.335
And this right over here, let's see,

00:00:07.335 --> 00:00:11.846
we have 1, 2, 3 carbons in our backbone

00:00:11.846 --> 00:00:15.431
so this would be meth eth propane.

00:00:15.431 --> 00:00:16.887
We all have single bonds right here,

00:00:16.887 --> 00:00:18.672
so this is propane.

00:00:18.672 --> 00:00:19.932
Let me write that out.

00:00:19.932 --> 00:00:23.973
This is, give myself some space, propane.

00:00:23.973 --> 00:00:25.671
And then on the number 2 carbon,

00:00:25.671 --> 00:00:28.570
I have both a methyl
group and a bromo group

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:31.732
and bromo comes before
methyl in alphabetical order.

00:00:31.732 --> 00:00:34.938
So I could write this as 2 bromo,

00:00:34.938 --> 00:00:38.441
2 bromo, 2 methyl,

00:00:38.441 --> 00:00:45.519
2 methyl, methyl propane.

00:00:45.519 --> 00:00:48.051
So that's this molecule that
we have right over here.

00:00:48.051 --> 00:00:49.250
Now what we're going to imagine,

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:50.444
it's sitting in some water

00:00:50.444 --> 00:00:53.320
and I have 1 water molecule
drawn right over here.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:56.339
Let's imagine that we have
this bromine right over here.

00:00:56.339 --> 00:00:57.649
It's pretty neutral.

00:00:57.649 --> 00:00:58.667
And it's neutral because it has-

00:00:58.667 --> 00:01:02.049
or it is neutral because
it has 7 valence electrons.

00:01:02.049 --> 00:01:04.685
1, 2, or you could say- or
it has the charge equivalent

00:01:04.685 --> 00:01:06.701
as 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:01:06.701 --> 00:01:08.599
And then it has half of this bond

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:10.685
that's composed of 2 electrons.

00:01:10.685 --> 00:01:14.301
So that's what's keeping
this neutral right over here.

00:01:14.301 --> 00:01:16.574
But we do know that bromine,

00:01:16.574 --> 00:01:20.172
well you know, it's not
completely unstable.

00:01:20.172 --> 00:01:22.458
If it were to take an electron,

00:01:22.458 --> 00:01:24.552
because that would get it
to 8 valence electrons,

00:01:24.552 --> 00:01:26.963
we know that it's more
electro-negative than carbon

00:01:26.963 --> 00:01:28.487
which means that if it's sharing a bond,

00:01:28.487 --> 00:01:32.576
it's more likely to take the
entire bond than carbon is.

00:01:32.576 --> 00:01:34.602
So let's imagine a scenario.

00:01:34.602 --> 00:01:36.952
Let's imagine a scenario where bromine

00:01:36.952 --> 00:01:41.058
takes these 2 carbons in
this bond right over here.

00:01:41.058 --> 00:01:43.984
And this isn't going to be a
super fast thing that happens

00:01:43.984 --> 00:01:45.710
because this molecule right over here,

00:01:45.710 --> 00:01:47.454
the 2 bromo 2 methyl propane

00:01:47.454 --> 00:01:48.823
is actually reasonably stable,

00:01:48.823 --> 00:01:50.028
so I'm not saying that this is

00:01:50.028 --> 00:01:51.123
going to just happen automatically.

00:01:51.123 --> 00:01:52.498
It's going to happen super fast,

00:01:52.498 --> 00:01:53.997
but it could happen.

00:01:53.997 --> 00:01:56.022
And so to show that this isn't going to be

00:01:56.022 --> 00:01:58.098
you know, only one-way reaction,

00:01:58.098 --> 00:02:00.067
I'll show that it's an equilibrium.

00:02:00.067 --> 00:02:03.410
So the equilibrium, I'll
draw 2 arrows like that.

00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:06.390
So, once this happens, the bromine

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:08.495
would turn into a bromide anion.

00:02:08.495 --> 00:02:10.564
So let me draw that right over here.

00:02:10.564 --> 00:02:12.506
So the bromide anion.

00:02:12.506 --> 00:02:16.466
So it's going to have 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6,

00:02:16.466 --> 00:02:19.611
and then both electrons
from that shared bond.

00:02:19.611 --> 00:02:22.692
Both electrons from that shared bond.

00:02:22.692 --> 00:02:26.972
It now has a negative 1 charge.

00:02:26.972 --> 00:02:28.114
Now if that happened,

00:02:28.114 --> 00:02:30.452
what would happen to this leftover,

00:02:30.452 --> 00:02:32.198
to I guess what's now going to be

00:02:32.198 --> 00:02:35.649
the thing that bromine

00:02:35.649 --> 00:02:37.659
was connected to I guess you could say.

00:02:37.659 --> 00:02:39.200
Let's draw that.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:42.857
So we have this carbon,
our number 2 carbon.

00:02:42.857 --> 00:02:45.890
We have CH3 right over there.

00:02:45.890 --> 00:02:49.153
Then we go back to a CH3

00:02:49.153 --> 00:02:51.586
and then we had this blue methyl group.

00:02:51.586 --> 00:02:53.815
So, I'll add this blue
methyl group right over here

00:02:53.815 --> 00:02:54.871
and the way I'm drawing it,

00:02:54.871 --> 00:02:57.187
it kind of pops out of the page.

00:02:57.187 --> 00:03:00.178
My best attempt to draw it
popping out of the page.

00:03:00.178 --> 00:03:05.034
So this is it popping out of the page.

00:03:05.034 --> 00:03:07.784
And now, what's its charge going to be?

00:03:07.784 --> 00:03:10.041
Well it just gave up half of this bond,

00:03:10.041 --> 00:03:12.890
the equivalent of an electron's charge.

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:15.071
So it just gave up, you
can kind of think of it,

00:03:15.071 --> 00:03:16.641
as giving up an electron,

00:03:16.641 --> 00:03:19.840
so this is going to
have a positive charge.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:22.880
This is going to have a positive charge.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:25.137
A positive charged carbon like this,

00:03:25.137 --> 00:03:27.658
we would call this a carbocation.

00:03:27.658 --> 00:03:34.405
So this right over here is a
carbocation, positive charge.

00:03:34.405 --> 00:03:37.939
And the reason why this is
not a crazy thing to happen

00:03:37.939 --> 00:03:39.842
is that this is a tertiary carbon,

00:03:39.842 --> 00:03:42.126
which means that it is
connected to 3 other carbons.

00:03:42.126 --> 00:03:43.612
1, 2, 3.

00:03:43.612 --> 00:03:45.777
A tertiary carbon, one
way to think about it,

00:03:45.777 --> 00:03:49.646
is that this positive
charge can kind of be shared

00:03:49.646 --> 00:03:51.764
with its brothers a little bit more.

00:03:51.764 --> 00:03:55.025
So tertiary, a tertiary
carbocation is more stable

00:03:55.025 --> 00:03:56.435
than a secondary and definitely

00:03:56.435 --> 00:03:57.942
more stable than a primary.

00:03:57.942 --> 00:03:58.796
A secondary would be

00:03:58.796 --> 00:04:00.284
if it was only connected to 2 carbons,

00:04:00.284 --> 00:04:02.245
but this is tertiary so
let me write this down.

00:04:02.245 --> 00:04:04.983
This is a tertiary carbocation.

00:04:04.983 --> 00:04:08.618
This carbon is connected
to 3 other carbons.

00:04:08.618 --> 00:04:10.631
That's where the tertiary comes from.

00:04:10.631 --> 00:04:12.918
So once again, it can happen.

00:04:12.918 --> 00:04:14.164
I'm not saying that this reaction's

00:04:14.164 --> 00:04:16.043
just going to go super
fast in that direction.

00:04:16.043 --> 00:04:18.345
That's why we did these equilibriums.

00:04:18.345 --> 00:04:20.917
These equilibrium arrows.

00:04:20.917 --> 00:04:23.494
Now let's bring this oxygen into play.

00:04:23.494 --> 00:04:26.481
So let's bring- now let's bring-

00:04:26.481 --> 00:04:30.595
sorry not the oxygen, let's
bring this water into play.

00:04:30.595 --> 00:04:33.476
So this water, as you can
imagine, the water's neutral

00:04:33.476 --> 00:04:36.794
and it seems pretty
reasonable in this state,

00:04:36.794 --> 00:04:41.051
but the oxygen end of the water does have

00:04:41.051 --> 00:04:42.800
a partial negative charge.

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:44.411
We've seen in the past.

00:04:44.411 --> 00:04:47.944
We've seen in the past that

00:04:47.944 --> 00:04:49.057
because oxygen is

00:04:49.057 --> 00:04:51.072
a lot more electronegative
than the hydrogens,

00:04:51.072 --> 00:04:52.561
that you have a partial negative side

00:04:52.561 --> 00:04:54.242
on the side of the oxygens

00:04:54.242 --> 00:04:56.445
and you have a partial positive charge

00:04:56.445 --> 00:04:59.820
on the side of the hydrogens.

00:04:59.820 --> 00:05:01.683
On the side of the hydrogens.

00:05:01.683 --> 00:05:04.044
And so you have this positive carbocation.

00:05:04.044 --> 00:05:05.847
