00:05:05.847 --> 00:05:08.565
So you can imagine that this molecule

00:05:08.565 --> 00:05:11.995
might be attracted to this nucleus.

00:05:11.995 --> 00:05:13.748
Now it's not going to be super attracted

00:05:13.748 --> 00:05:15.811
the way that an hydroxide anion would.

00:05:15.811 --> 00:05:18.232
A hydroxide anion has
a full negative charge.

00:05:18.232 --> 00:05:20.189
This only has a little
partial negative charge.

00:05:20.189 --> 00:05:21.720
But it could still be
attracted to something

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:23.676
very positive like this.

00:05:23.676 --> 00:05:26.344
So in this situation, the water molecule

00:05:26.344 --> 00:05:28.876
is a weak nucleophile.

00:05:28.876 --> 00:05:32.038
So this is a weak nucleophile.

00:05:32.038 --> 00:05:34.686
Not as strong as a hydroxide anion

00:05:34.686 --> 00:05:35.900
that has a full negative charge,

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:37.528
but if it sees something
positive like this

00:05:37.528 --> 00:05:39.111
and it bumps in the right way,

00:05:39.111 --> 00:05:41.789
you could imagine that one of these pairs

00:05:41.789 --> 00:05:45.632
of this oxygen would then go-

